			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				A verant employee? (LOL) I just started playing two months ago. So, no, I've never exploited blackburrow. My most powerful character is a level 9, non-twinked necro. This reminds me of the people crying because Verant took the sledgehammer to them for getting their account-sharing habits reported. Jesus Christ, when you signed on, you agreed NOT TO DO THAT. You did it anyway, now you pay the consequences.<BR>
<BR>
I'll address a few points:<BR>
<BR>
Yes, Verant SHOULD reward people for finding and reporting such massive bugs. Conquest found a bug, and then-- wait for it-- DID NOT REPORT IT. They EXPLOITED it instead. Go read the Everqust terms of service. It says plain as day that if you find a bug, you are under obligation to immediately report it via the /bug command and not use it to your advantage. Conquest broke that rule, they knew they were breaking the rule, they rode the rocket as a result. Lots of people break the rules without getting caught? Why, yes, they do, because the player-to-GM ratio is something like 500 to one. Verant made one mistake here, and it was trying to justify themselves. Conquest broke the rules, Conquest was punished. End of story. Very simple. Also, only two people were actually banned-- these were people who had been caught using exploits before. They weren't first-time offenders. They knew what they were doing, they had been caught before, they knew what would happen, they paid the price. Everyone else was only suspended for a while.<BR>
<BR>
And, yes, the entire guild was disbanded, even though not all guild members were online and cheating at the time, because A) the vast majority of the guild WAS online and cheating, and B) the leader was among those online and cheating.<BR>
<BR>
Jesus, I wish Sega had come down as hard on cheaters in Phantasy Star Online. Maybe if they had I'd still be playing that game.<BR>
<BR>
The sad fact is that half a dozen jackasses can ruin an entire server's economy within a couple of days if allowed to do so. The ONLY way to deal with cheaters is by using draconian measures to stamp them out, or to let them run wild. PSO has proven definitively that half-measures simply do not work. It'd be nice if people could simply be pulled out of the zone and slapped on the wrist, but that doesn't work. Heck, two of the Conquest members had already been slapped enough times that Verant decided not to fool with them anymore and just cut them loose.<BR>
<BR>
Just the 2cp of someone who's more concerned with maintaining the integrity of the game than in the fate of a double-handful of intentional cheaters.<BR>
<BR>
--<BR>
Khailen, lv9 half-elf Paladin of Rodcet Nife<BR>
Saori, lv9 dark elf Necromancer of Rodcet Nife
